Name: United States Real GDP in 2012 Dollars
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1789 To Dec 1946
Quarterly From Mar 1947 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Data are in the billions of constant US Dollars.Sources: Annual data before 1929 are taken from Historical Statistics of the United States, Colonial times to 1970, Washington: U.S. Dept. of Commerce, and B.R. Mitchell, International Historical Statistics: The Americas 1750-1992, Fourth Edition, New York: Stockton Press, 1998; Bureau of the Census, U.S. Govt. Print. Off., 1975; Quarterly data are from the US Bureau of Economic Analysis which calculates the GDP data. Notes: Data are in billions of US Dollars. Data are disseminated in current prices and in real terms, with corresponding price indexes, for GDP and GNP by expenditure category; in current prices for national income, personal income and saving; and, in real terms for disposable personal income and per capita disposable income. Detailed data on GDP are published for the following expenditure categories: personal consumption expenditure; private fixed investment in structures;private fixed investment in equipment and software; change in private inventories; exports; imports; Federal government consumption expenditures and gross investment; state and local government consumption expenditure and gross investment. Detailed components of national income, personal income, and consumption of fixed capital are also published. Current price estimates are generally presented in billions of dollars; real measures are presented in both index form and in dollars and are calculated using the chained Fisher index formula (reference year, 1996). Quarterly estimates are seasonally adjusted and at annual rates. The geographic coverage of the data is the 50 States and the District of Columbia. All legal activities are covered (certain non-market activities by imputation). Activities reflect the entire period (year or quarter). GDP is recorded on a production timing basis; consistent with production, national income and its components are largely on an accrual basis; personal taxes are on a cash basis and personal income is largely on a cash basis. The personal sector covers households and nonprofit institutions serving individuals; the business sector covers, in addition to businesses organized for profit, mutual financial institutions, private noninsured pension funds, cooperatives, government enterprises, and nonprofit institutions that primarily serve business. Basic data include economic censuses taken at 5-year intervals; annual, quarterly, and monthly statistical surveys; decennial censuses of housing and residential finance; budgetary and administrative information, including tabulations of tax returns; and private trade sources. The United States has either already adopted, or is moving towards adopting, the most important changes included in the 1993 SNA.Source: Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis. The data is collected from the FRED database. The FRED database uses data from the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System, the Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia, the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, The White House Council of Economic Advisors and Office of Management and Budget, the Congressional Budget Office, the U.S. Department of Commerce, the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, the Bureau of Labor Statistics and the U.S. Department of the Treasury.

The disseminated data for Germany include data on: current price GDP in billions of EUR; constant price GDP (1995=100) in billions of EUR; per-capita GDP; GNI; disposable income; and national income in EUR. The following breakdowns are disseminated: (1) Origination of the gross domestic product (BIP): nominal and real results according to six economic sectors (agriculture, forestry, and fishing; manufacturing, including energy; construction; trade and transport; financial, renting and business activities; and other service activities. The most important base statistics for the quarterly calculations are the production index, monthly construction reporting, monthly foreign trade statistics and other monthly and quarterly statistics.

Name: Brazil Real GDP in 2010 Reais
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Dec 1989
Quarterly From Mar 1990 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Source: Cepalstat
Notes: Quarterly data are disseminated (in millions of Reais (R$)) on GDP in current prices and annually-chained volume index of GDP as well as GDP implicit deflators.The data are published in the form of value, numerical indices and rates of change. The data are compiled by the production method and cover the entire economy of Brazil. The GDP in current prices measures the total amount of the goods and services for final use produced during the quarter before deduction of consumption of fixed capital. Quarterly data are adjusted to annual data using a bench marking procedure. The quarterly GDP estimates are close to the recommendations of the United Nations System of National Accounts, SNA 1993. All transactions defined in the SNA for production (commercial and non-commercial transactions) are recorded on an accrual basis, except government revenues, which are on a cash basis. Noncommercial transactions are measured by production costs. Imputed rents are measured by the market price of similar units. Breakdowns of GDP in current prices and annually-chained volume index of GDP as well as GDP implicit deflators are disseminated for 4 groups (Agropecuaria, Industria, Servicos e Doummy Financeiro), and breakdowns of annually-chained volume index of GDP dissagregated by 14 subgroups (Crops, Animal Production, Plant Extraction, Mineral Extraction, Manufacturing, Building, Public utility industrial services, Commerce, Transportation, Communications, Financial Institutions, Rents, Public Administration and Other Services). The classifications follow ISIC-Rev. 2 and the data for all activities are seasonally adjusted. The seasonally-adjusted data are obtained using the X12-Arima method.

Name: Australia Real GDP in 2007-2008 Dollars
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1820 To Mar 1960
Quarterly From Jun 1960 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Chain volume measures are referenced to 2007/08 values.There is a single measure of gross domestic product, GDP. For periods in which the components of GDP do not balance, statistical discrepancies have been introduced and GDP is calculated as the average of estimates from the income, expenditure and production approaches. For years in which balanced supply-use tables are available, the annual statistical discrepancies are zero. Non-farm GDP is GDP less gross farm output. Primary production is the sum of agriculture, forestry & fishing and mining. Production and distribution is the sum of: manufacturing; electricity, gas, water & waste services; construction; wholesale trade; retail trade; and transport, postal & warehousing. Other (mainly services) production is the sum of: accommodation & food services; information media & telecommunications; financial & insurance services; rental, hiring & real estate services; professional, scientific & technical services; administrative & support services; public administration & safety; education & training; health care & social assistance; arts & recreation services; other services; and ownership of dwellings. Real gross domestic income' (real GDI) is calculated by adjusting gross domestic product for the effect of the terms of trade. The terms of trade is the implicit price deflator of exports of goods and services divided by the implicit price deflator of imports of goods and services. Real gross national income is the income which accrues to persons, enterprises and other organisations regarded as residents of a country. Real gross national income equals real GDI adjusted for net primary income flows from abroad.

Name: Chile Real GDP in 2008 Pesos
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1810 To Dec 1990
Quarterly From Mar 1991 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Source: Central Bank of Chile. Annual data are from DÃ­az, LÃ¼ders, and Wagner (2010: chapter 2)
Notes: Data are disseminated in Chilean pesos for Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in current prices and constant 1986 prices. (The scale of data presentation, millions or billions of Chilean pesos, is specified in the relevant publications). The data cover the entire economy of Chile. The data for GDP in constant 1986 prices are broken down by productive sector (classified according to CIIU, Rev. 2) and by major expenditure category showing: gross fixed capital formation, rest of domestic demand, and exports and imports of goods and services. The data for GDP in current prices are broken down only by major expenditure category showing the same breakdown as GDP (by expenditure side) at constant prices. The basic data are obtained from surveys, administrative registers, and other sources. In general, the data are compiled following the guidelines of the "System of National Accounts 1993" (SNA '93). The constant 1986 data cover the period since 1986. (The previous series in constant 1977 prices was compiled for the period from 1980 through 1993.). The current price data cover the period since 1990. On February 25, 1998, revised figures of national accounts covering the 1989-96 period were released. These data include an important methodological modification, in which direct investment income is registered on an accrual basis instead of on a cash basis. Data on global GDP, seasonally adjusted, are also published.

Name: Colombia Real GDP in 2015 Pesos
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1900 To Dec 1993
Quarterly From Mar 1994 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Colombia changed their GDP methodology in 1975, 1994, 2000 and 2005.  This creates a larger than normal change in GDP in 1994, changing GDP from 57982 billion to 67532 billion.Notes: The data are disseminated in millions of Colombian pesos on GDP in current and constant (1994) prices. The annual data are disseminated as a level, and the quarterly data from Q1 1994 are published as a level, as a percentage change, and as indices. The data are compiled by production method and cover the entire economy, including estimations for sectors with tie to the illegal economy. The data are broken down by sector of economic activity, by institutional sector, and by final supply and demand. The breakdown of the principal sectors of economic activity is disseminated in both current and constant 1994 prices at the one-digit level of the ISIC. The breakdown includes the following: agriculture; mining; manufacturing industry; electricity, gas and water; construction and public works; trade, restaurants and hotels; transport and communications; financial establishments, real estate insurance and business services; social, Communal, and Personal services. The breakdown by institutional sector is published in current prices only and shows: households and private nonprofit institutions; general government; public and private financial institutions; and public and private nonfinancial companies and quasi-companies. Data on implicit price indices and data on GDP at factor cost are also published. The data are prepared according to the recommendations of the 1993 edition of the United Nations System of National Accounts

Name: Hong Kong Real GDP in 2009 Dollars
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1950 To Dec 1972
Quarterly From Mar 1973 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Source: Hong Kong Monetary Authority

Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of Hong Kong dollars on GDP in current and constant 2000 prices, together with implicit price deflators. The data cover the territory administered by the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and all economic sectors of the economy. Data on transactions with the mainland of China are treated as external transactions. The quarterly constant price GDP figures are compiled using both the expenditure and production approaches, whereas the quarterly current price figures are compiled by expenditure approach. Current price GDP by production approach is compiled annually. The GDP compiled by expenditure approach is adopted as the single measure of GDP. The following breakdowns of GDP are compiled and disseminated: (a) by expenditure component, which includes private consumption expenditure; government consumption expenditure; gross domestic fixed capital formation; changes in inventories; exports of goods; exports of services; imports of goods; and imports of services. (b) by economic activity, in which economic activities are classified according to the Hong Kong Standard Industrial Classification version 1.1 (HSIC V1.1), with two additional items, viz. ownership of premises and Financial Intermediation Services Indirectly Measured (FISIM). The concepts and definitions follow the 1993 "System of National Accounts" (SNA). Seasonally adjusted data are also published.

Name: India Real GDP in 2010 Rupees
Periodicity:

Quarterly From Mar 1996 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Source: Ministry of Finance, Department of Economic Affairs.Definition: Data are in the process to be compiled according to SNA93. India presently uses a mix of the SNA68 and the SNA93. Name: Indonesia Real GDP in 2010 Rupiah
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Dec 1992
Quarterly From Mar 1993 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Annual data are from van der Eng (2008: 31-33; 2009: 29-30). Data are disseminated on quarterly GDP at current and constant 1993 market prices, in billions of Indonesian Rupiah, compiled by both the production approach and the expenditure approach. The GDP data cover the entire economy. The data compiled using the production approach are disseminated with a breakdown of total GDP by production sector as follows: agriculture; mining and quarrying; manufacturing industry; electricity, gas and clean water; construction; trade, hotels and restaurants; transportation and communication; finance, leasing and business services; and other services. The data compiled using the expenditure approach are disseminated with a breakdown of total GDP by expenditure category as follows: consumption expenditure by household; consumption expenditure by government; gross fixed capital formation; change in stock; exports of goods and services; and imports of goods and services. Data on GNP are also available after GDP is added to net factor income from abroad and data on national income as well after GNP is deducted by net indirect taxes and depreciation. The data are compiled in accordance with the "System of National Accounts 1968". The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Israel Real GDP in 2010 Sheqalim
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1950 To Dec 1979
Quarterly From Mar 1980 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of NIS (new Israeli sheqels) on GDP in current and constant 1995 prices. The data are compiled using the expenditure method, and cover the entire economy. A breakdown of GDP in both current and constant prices is disseminated as follows: private consumption expenditure; general government consumption expenditure; gross fixed capital formation; increase in stocks; exports and imports of goods and services. Current and constant price data on GDP for the whole economy and GDP for the business sector are also disseminated. The data are defined and classified according to the System of National Accounts (SNA 1993), except that the definition of the product at market prices differs from the SNA definition in the following ways: (1) the value of the product does not cover taxes on imports; and (2) the value of the product includes other revenue components received by the exporters. Data on GDP including net taxes on imports are also published to enable international comparisons.  The data are disseminated in both original and seasonally adjusted formats.

Name: Korea (Republic of) Real GDP in 2005 Won

Quarterly From Mar 1960 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated in billions of Korean won on GDP estimates at current and 2000 constant prices, together with deflators. As the basic method of compilation, the production approach, the expenditure approach and the income approach are used. The data are compiled primarily by the production approach considering accuracy and availability of the source data.  The following breakdowns of the current and constant price GDP data are disseminated:  (1) A breakdown by kind of economic activity into: agriculture forestry and fishing; mining and quarrying; manufacturing; electricity, gas and water supply; construction; wholesale and retail trade, restaurants and hotels; transport, storage and communication; financial intermediation, real estate, rental and business activities; public administration and defense, compulsory social security; education; health and social work; other service activities; taxes less subsidies on products. (2) A breakdown by expenditure category into: final consumption expenditure; gross capital formation; exports and imports of goods and services; and statistical discrepancy. Data on savings at current prices are also disseminated. The national accounts data are compiled following the analytical framework, concepts, definitions, accounting conventions, and classifications of the System of National Accounts 1993.  The data are published in both original and seasonally-adjusted format.

Name: Peru Real GDP in 2010 Soles
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1896 To Dec 1978
Quarterly From Mar 1979 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of nuevos soles on Gross Domestic Product (GDP) compiled by the expenditure method at current prices and at constant 1994 prices. GDP data compiled by the production method are available at constant 1994 prices only. The data cover the entire economy.  The economic activities considered for the estimates of quarterly national accounts are agriculture and livestock; fishing; mining and fuel (which is divided in metallic mining and fuel); manufacturing (which comprises primary and non-primary industries); electricity and water; construction; trade and other services. GDP by expenditure categories considers all the components of global demand and supply: private consumption, public consumption, private investment, public investment, changes in inventories, exports and imports of goods and non-financial services. Although the National Institute of Statistics and Informatics (INEI) has the responsability of preparing the national accounts, the Quarterly GDP data are prepared by the Central Reserve Bank of Peru (BCRP) using the expenditure method.  These estimates are consistent with the annual estimates published by the INEI and are derived from the monthly GDP results, calculated by the INEI using the production method. The classification of the data follows the 1993 edition of the UN System of National Accounts (SNA).  The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Philippines Real GDP in 2015 Pesos
Periodicity:

Metadata: Notes: GDP and GNP estimates are disseminated at current levels and constant 1985 prices; in million of pesos, together with growth rates, implicit price deflators and percent distribution by industry and expenditure items. The estimates are presented in both the production and expenditure approach and cover the entire economy of the Philippines. GDP based on production is broken down by economic activity while factor incomes are estimated by institutional sector. GDP by expenditure share is disaggregated as follows: personal consumption; government consumption; fixed capital formation which includes construction, durable equipment and breeding stocks and orchard development; changes in stocks; export of goods (top 22 commodities) and services; and imports of goods (top 15 commodities) and services. Name: Portugal Real GDP in 2010 Euros
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1850 To Dec 1976
Quarterly From Mar 1977 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of Euro on GDP in current prices and in constant 1995 prices, compiled by the expenditure and production methods. The data cover the entire economy of Portugal. The expenditure-based data are broken down into: private final consumption, collective consumption, gross fixed capital formation, imports of goods and services, and exports of goods and services. Private consumption (in the economic territory) is divided into: agriculture and food goods, durable goods, and current private consumption. Gross Capital Formation is divided into Gross Fixed Capital Formation, Acquisitions Less Disposable of Valuables and Changes in Stocks. Gross fixed capital formation is divided into: agriculture products, machinery and other equipment, transport material, construction, and other products. Data on gross value added in constant 1995 prices is disseminated for the following activities: agriculture, hunting, forestry and fishing; electricity, gas and water; industry; trade, restaurants and hotels; transports and communications; banking, insurance and renting activities; other services. The estimates for all activities, except agriculture, and all expenditure categories, except collective consumption, are based on primary quarterly data collected during the period, and are compiled using econometric techniques. The data for agriculture and collective consumption are based on primary annual data. The data are estimated according to the ESA (European System of Accounts) 95. The basic statistics are seasonally adjusted.

Name: Netherlands Real GDP in 2010 Euros
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1820 To Dec 1976
Quarterly From Mar 1977 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Sources: In 1990 the Dutch Science Foundation granted Prof.dr J.L. van Zanden a subsidy for the research programme "Reconstructing National Accounts of the Netherlands and the analysis of the development of the Dutch Economy in the period 1800-1940". From then onwards this programme resulted in a great number of articles and dissertations which provide a deeper understanding the the dynamics of long-term economic growth. To reconstruct national income extensive data concerning income, prices, foreign trade, production, employment and capital formation were collected and processed.The calculations of output were the starting point of the project. Initially the research was focussed on the estimations of value added in agriculture, industry and services. Major research was undertaken to reconstruct the movement of output, inputs and prices in various sectors of the economy. The work on capital formation has been equal importance. Other categories of expenditure were estimated either directly from primary source material (e.g. government expenditure) or indirect by combining data on output and foreign trade (private consumer expenditure). The income side of the accounting system was the object of two separate projects, one on wages, salaries and income inequality and another on income from capital. See the research publication Dutch GNP and its components, 1800-1913, for a description of the National Account Project (in pfd, 763 KB).See http://nationalaccounts.niwi.knaw.nl/start.htmNotes: Data are disseminated in millions of Dutch guilders on GDP at current and constant 1995 prices. The GDP data cover the entire economy. The following breakdowns are disseminated: by expenditure category, by productive sectors, NACE (rev.1), and by cost components. The breakdown by major expenditure category includes the following components: consumption expenditure by households and by government, consumption expenditure, individual and collective, gross fixed capital formation by government and by corporations, changes in stocks, and exports and imports of goods and services. The breakdowns are disseminated both in current and in constant prices. QNA uses a make-use table as an instrument for the integration of short-term statistical data on output, expenditure and income.  The data are compiled in accordance with the methodology set out in ESA95. The data are disseminated in both unadjusted and seasonally adjusted formats. However, the seasonally adjusted data are available only at a high aggregated level, such as, the supply and disposition of goods and services, gross fixed capital formation, change in inventories, and, export of goods and services.

Name: Norway Real GDP in 2010 Krone
Periodicity:

Quarterly From Mar 1966 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Sources: Grytten, O.H. (2004). ""The gross domestic product for Norway 1830-2003"", 241-288, Historical Monetary Statistics for Norway 1819-2003, Norges Bank Occasional Papers no. 35, Oslo, 2004
Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of Norwegian kroner (NOK) on GDP in current prices and in a combination of annually-chained and constant prices. The annually-chained price basis is used when the final annual national accounts of the previous year are available to provide the base for prices. If the final annual national accounts of the previous year are not available, the quarterly GDP data are reported in constant prices using the year of the latest final national accounts as the base year. (For example, if the latest final annual accounts are available for 1996, the quarterly GDP data for the period up to and including Q4 1997 are reported on an annually-chained basis, and the quarterly GDP for the period from Q1 1998 onwards are reported using 1996 constant prices.) The GDP data cover the entire Norwegian economy and are compiled using both by expenditure and production methods.
Breakdowns are disseminated on final expenditure categories and gross domestic product in current and constant prices, and the percentage changes in volume and prices. Final consumption is broken down by institutional sectors: households; non-profit institutions serving households (NPISHs); and central and local government. Gross fixed capital formation is broken down by main industries: petroleum activities; ocean transport; manufacturing and mining; other goods-producing industries; dwelling services; other market services; and general government services. Exports and imports are broken down by main categories of products. Data are also disseminated showing breakdowns on productive sectors, including breakdowns for aggregate industries, both in current and constant prices and in percentage changes in volume and prices. Data on saving and gross national income are published annually only, but are implicitly available on a quarterly basis. The quarterly data are not seasonally adjusted, but some seasonally adjusted annual series are published in ÃƒËœkonomiske Analyser.

For this purpose, Demetra version 2.0 was applied.

Name: Great Britain Real GDP in 2008 Pounds
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1270 To Dec 1954
Quarterly From Mar 1955 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Data from 1270 to 1870 are from Stephen Broadberry, and Bruce Campbell, Alexander Klein, Mark Overton and Bas van Leeuwen, "British Economic Growth, 1270-1870: An Output -based Approach"; http://www.lse.ac.uk/economicHistory/whosWho/profiles/sbroadberry.aspxData before 1955 is from B. R. Mitchell, International Historical Statistics: Europe 1750-2000, Fourth Edition, Stockton Press, 2003. Notes: Data are disseminated in three main formats: the "Four Week" estimate; the "Eight Week" estimate; and the "Twelve Week Estimate". The last two meet the SDDS requirements and publish current and constant price data in millions of pounds Sterling. (1) The "Four Week" estimate publishes only constant price output analysis at basic prices in index number form with a base year of 1995. The categories for which data are published include: Distribution, Hotels and Catering, Total Services, and Gross Domestic Product. Movements of output components at basic prices are used as an indicator of growth at market prices at this early stage. (2) The "Eight Week" estimate publishes a fuller "output" analysis, in both current and constant 1995 prices in millions of pounds Sterling. Detailed data are published showing breakdowns by productive activity, by expenditure category and by income. (a) The breakdown by productive activity shows estimates of output for: Agriculture, Hunting Forestry and Fishing; Mining and Quarrying, including oil and gas extraction; Manufacturing; Electricity, gas and water supply; Total Index of Production; Construction; Transport and Communication; Finance and Business Services; and Government and other services, as well as the aggregates published in the Four Week estimates.  (b) The breakdown by expenditure category is published in both current and constant market prices for: Household Final Expenditure; Non-profit Institutions Serving Households (NPISH) Final Expenditure; General Government Final Consumption; Gross Fixed Capital Formation; Change in Inventories; Acquisition less Disposals of Valuables; Total Exports; and Total Imports."  (c) The "income analysis" breakdown shows the following aggregates: Compensation of Employees; Gross Operating Surplus of Corporations; and Other Income. (3) The "Twelve Week" estimates publish full quarterly national accounts, including all the breakdowns indicated above, with a further disaggregation of the Income and Expenditure components, and with current, capital and financial accounts for the private nonfinancial corporations sector, household income, expenditure and saving. Estimates for Gross Domestic Product and Gross Value Added are compiled on various bases, for example, at current market prices, at basic prices, at factor cost, at constant 1995 prices and as indices where 1995=100. The data in current and constant prices are disseminated in millions of pounds Sterling. The data are published in both seasonally adjusted and unadjusted formats and are compiled in accordance with the methodology set out in ESA95.

Name: Czech Republic Real GDP in 2010 Korun
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1985 To Dec 1993
Quarterly From Mar 1994 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data on gross domestic product (GDP) are disseminated at current prices, previous year's average prices, and 1995 constant prices, all as absolute values (CZK million) and as the growth rate from year to year. The data cover the entire economy of the Czech Republic. As to constant prices, they were 1995 constant prices up to March 2004 (the 4th quarter 2003 GDP estimate). In June 2004 (the 1st quarter 2004 GDP estimate) the data at previous year average prices and 2000 constant prices were published. Since September 2004 (the 2nd quarter 2004 GDP estimate) the data at previous year average prices and at the prices of 1995 obtained by chain-linking are published. The annual overlap technique is used for chain-linking.   The data are compiled in accordance with the methodology set out in ESA 1995. Data on GDP are disseminated broken down by expenditure categories as follows: household expenditures; non-profit institution expenditures; government institutions expenditures (individual and collective); gross fixed capital formation; changes in stocks; exports of goods; exports of services; imports of goods; and imports of services. Data on gross value added broken down by NACE categories and data on the encouraged components of saving and gross national income are also published. The data since 1994 have been published both as non-adjusted and seasonally adjusted ones. In addition, the indices derived from seasonally adjusted time series of the GDP expenditure categories are published. The TRAMO/SEATS method (Demetra 2.0) is used for the seasonal adjustments. The seasonally adjusted time series were not published in June 2004. The reason was that the historical revision of the quarterly NA was not completed in June. The seasonally adjusted data on GDP and GDP expenditures (only from the year 1995) were released on September 14, 2004. The completed seasonally adjusted data on GDP resources and expenditures were again released on December 10, 2004 (comprising time-series from the year 1995). For the first time, a correction for a number of working days in individual periods was performed on selected time series for which the influence of different numbers of working days is statistically significant.

Metadata: Source: K. Ohkawa et al., Long Term economic Statistics of Japan Since 1868, v. 14 (Tokyo, 1979). Data are for GNP to 1930 and GDP thereafter.Notes: Data are disseminated in thousand millions of Yen on nominal and real GDP, together with the implicit deflators. The data are compiled using the GDP by expenditure for flow accounts and the private capital assets for stock accounts, both of which cover the entire Japanese economy.
